MissionCommands.Message: Welcome to the Mercury-Redstone 4 historical mission. The cockpit is ready for full internal power and final checks.
[Complete the Full Internal Power (T-10) checklist]
[Follow the in-game steps to complete the Final cheks]
Capcom, this is Liberty Bell 7, how do you read?
Reading you loud and clear, Bell 7. How me?
Reading you loud and clear.
Roger.
[Remove Time Zero cover]
What's the count, Stoney?
Roger.
Okay, 1:30. Mark.
[Garble] Check your periscope filter is at MAG at this time. [Right click the Magnitude selector]
Okay, roger. Mag is, mag and filters are okay.
Roger.
No sun in your eyes?
No sun in my eyes.
Real fine.
Okay, coming up on one minute. Two, one, mark.
Okay, have a good trip [garble].
Roger.
35 [garble].
30 seconds.
[Garble]
Okay. Periscope is in, 23 amps [39 in this capsule].
[Garble] 20.
Lift-off.
Ah, Roger. This is Liberty Bell 7. The clock is operating.
Loud and clear, José. Don't cry too much.
Oke-doke.
OK, it's a nice ride up to now.
Loud and clear.
Roger.
OK. The fuel is go; about 1.25 g's. Cabin pressure is just coming off the peg. The O2 is go. We have 26 amps.
Roger. Pitch 88, the trajectory is good.
Roger, looks good here.
OK, there. We're starting to pick up a little bit of the noise and vibration; not bad, though, at all.
OK. The fuel is go. 1½ g's. Cabin is 8. The O2 is go. 27 amps.
[And ..] Pitch is … [4, 5] ... Pitch is 77. Trajectory is go.
Roger. Cabin pressure is still about 6 and dropping slightly. Looks like she's going to hold at about 5.5.
Believe me, the oxygen is go.
Cabin pressure holding 5.5.
Roger. Roger.
This is Liberty Bell 7. Fuel is go. 2 ½ g's. Cabin pressure 5.5. Oxygen is go.
Main 25.
Isolated. Isolated is 28. We are go.
Roger. Pitch is 62. Trajectory is good.
Roger. It looks good in here.

Everything is good. Cabin pressure is holding. Suit pressure is OK. 2 minutes and we got 4 g's. Fuel is go. Ah, feel the hand controller move just a hair there. Cabin pressure is holding. Oxygen is go. 25 amps.
Roger, we have go here.
[And I see a star!] Stand by for cutoff.
There went the tower.
[Chase] Roger, there went the tower, affirm.
Roger.
Squibs are off.
Roger.
There went posigrades, capsule has separated. We are at zero g and turning around and the sun is really bright.
Roger, cap sep is green, turnaround started, manual handle out.
[Apply some extra roll target for the ASCS here? 15 degrees off.]
Manual handle is out. The sky is very, very black. The capsule is coming around into orbit attitude. The roll is a little bit slow.
Roger.
I haven't seen a booster anyplace. OK, rate command is coming on. I'm in orbit attitude, I'm pitching up.
[Switching to Manual Proportion]
Roger, rate command is coming on. You're trying manual pitch.
[During next conversation: Null the roll first, then pitch up to +24 in pitch, kill rates.]
OK, I got roll back. OK, I'm at 24 in pitch.
Roger, your IP is right on, Gus, right on.
OK. I'm having a little trouble with rate, ah, with the manual control.
Roger.
If I can get her stabilized here, all axes are working all right.
Roger. Understand manual control is good.
Roger, it's - it's sort of sluggish, more than I expected.
[Flight Plan item: Yaw 45 degrees to the left using horizon as reference attitude]
OK, I'm yawing.
Roger, yaw.
[Stop at 45 degrees Yaw]
OK, coming back in yaw. I'm a little bit late there.
Roger. Reading you loud and clear, Gus.

There's a lot of stuff floating around up here. ... OK, I'm going to skip the yaw, ah, or roll because I'm a little bit late and I'm going to try this left yaw maneuver. About all I can really see is clouds. I haven't seen any land anyplace yet.
Roger, you're on the window. Are you trying a yaw maneuver?
I'm trying the yaw maneuver and I'm on the window. It's such a fascinating view out the window you just can't help but look out that way.
I understand.
4 plus 30, Gus.
[4 plus 30, he's looking out the window. A-OK.]
I can see the coast but I can't identify anything.
Roger, 4 plus 40 Gus.
OK, let me get back here to retro attitude. Retro sequence has started.
Roger, retro sequence has started. Go to retro attitude.
[Quickly maneuver to retro attitude. Roll: 0, Pitch: -34, Yaw: 0]
Right, we'll see if I'm bad, not in very good shape here.
Got 15 seconds, plenty of time, I'll give you a mark at 5:10.
OK, retro attitude is still green.
Retros on my mark, 3, 2, 1, mark.
OK, there's 1 [Retro 1] firing, there's 1 firing.  [Roger, retro 1.] There's 2 firing, nice little boost. There went 3. [Roger, 3, all retros are fired.] Roger, roger.
Roger, retrojettison armed.
Retro jettison is armed, going to rate command.
Roger, understand manual fuel handle is in.
Manual fuel handle is in, mark, going to HF.
Roger, HF.
Liberty Bell 7, this is Cap Com on HF, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5. How do you read 7?
This is Cap Com on HF, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5. How do you read 7?
[Maneuver to reentry attitude: roll: 0, pitch: +34, yaw: 0]

(no voice): Here, do you read me, do you read me on HF? … Going back to U … Boy is that … Retro, I'm back on UHF, and, ah, the jett … the retros have jettisoned. Now I can see the Cape and, oh boy, that is some sight. I can't see too much.
Roger, I am on UHF high, do you read me?
Roger, reading you loud and clear on UHF high, can you confirm retrojettison?
Going to reentry attitude [keep maneuvering+maintain reentry attitude]
Roger. Retros are jettisoned, scope has retracted, you're going to reentry attitude.
Affirmative.
Bell 7 from Cap Com, your IP is right on.
Roger. I'm in reentry attitude. [At least you should be there now]
Roger, how does it look out the window now?
Ah, the sun is coming in and so all I can see really is just, ah, just darkness. The sky is very black.
Roger, you have some more time to look if you like.
7 from Cap Com, how do you feel up there?
I feel very good, auto fuel is 90, manual is 50.
Roger, 0.05 g in 10.
OK.
OK, everything is very good. I got 0.05 g and roll rate has started.
Roger.

Got a pitch rate in here, OK, g's are starting to build. [Roger, reading you loud and clear] Roger, g's are building, we're up to 6. There's 9. There's about 10; the handle is out from under it; here I got a little pitch rate coming back down through 7.
Roger, still sound good.
OK, the altimeter is active at 65.
Okay, I'm getting some contrails, evidently shock wave, 50,000 feet; I'm feeling good. I'm very good, everything is fine. 45,000, do you still read?
Affirmative. Still reading you. You sound good.
OK, 40,000 feet, do you read?
35,000 feet, if you read me.
30,000 feet, everything is good, everything is good.
Approaching drogue chute attitude.
There's the drogue chute. The periscope has extended.
OK, we're coming down to 15,000 feet, if anyone reads. We're on emergency flow rate, can see out the periscope OK. The drogue chute is good.
There's 13,000 feet.

There goes the main chute, it's reefed; main chute is good; main chute is good; rate of descent coming down, coming down to – there's 40 feet per second, 30 feet per, 32 feet per second on the main chute, and the landing bag is out green.
Hello, does anybody read Liberty Bell
Liberty Bell 7, Liberty Bell 7, this is Atlantic Ship Cap Com. Read you loud and clear. Our telemetry confirms your events. Over.
Atlantic Ship Cap Com, this is Liberty Bell 7, how do you read me? Over.
Read you loud and clear. Loud and clear. Over.
Liberty Bell 7, Liberty Bell 7. This is Atlantic Ship Cap Com. How do you read me? Over.
Atlantic Ship. Atlantic Ship Cap Com, this is Liberty Bell 7, I read you loud and clear, how me? Over.
Roger, Bell 7, read you loud and clear, your status looks good, your systems look good, we confirm your events. Over.
Ah, roger, and confirm the fuel has dumped. Over.
Roger, confirm again, confirm again, has your auto fuel dumped? Over.
Auto fuel and manual fuel has dumped.
Roger, roger.
And I'm in the process of putting the pins back in the door at this time.
OK, I'm passing down through 6,000 feet, everything is good, ah.
I'm going to open my face plate.

Hello, I can't get one, I can't get one door pin back in. I've tried and tried and I can't get it back in. And I'm coming, ATS, I'm passing through 5,000 feet and I don't think I have one of the door pins in.
Roger, Bell 7, roger.
Do you have any word from the recovery troops?
Liberty Bell 7, this is Card File 23, we are heading directly toward you.
ATS, this is Cap – this is Liberty Bell 7. Do you have any word from the recovery troops?
Negative, Bell 7, negative. Do you have any transmission to MCC? Over.
Ah, roger, you might make a note that there is one small hole in my chute. It looks like it's about 6 inches by 6 inches - it's sort of a, actually it's a triangular rip, I guess.
Ah, roger, roger.
I'm passing through 3,000 feet, and all the fuses are in flight condition; ASCS is normal, auto; we're on rate command; gyros are normal; auto retrojettison is armed; squibs are armed all.
Four fuel handles are in. Decompress and recompress are in. Retro delay is normal. Cabin lights are both. TM is on.

Rescue aids is auto; landing bag is auto; retract scope is auto; retroattitude is auto. All the three, five pull strings are in. Going through some clouds to 2,000 feet. ATS, I'm at 2,000 feet; everything is normal.
Roger, Bell 7, what is your rate of descent again? Over.
The rate of descent is varying between 28 and 30 feet per second.
Ah, roger, roger, and once again verify your fuel has dumped. Over.
OK. My max g was about 10.2; altimeter is 1,000; cabin pressure is coming towards 15.
And I'm getting ready for impact here. Can see the water coming right on up.
Liberty Bell 7, Liberty Bell 7, this is Atlantic Cap Com, do you read me? Over.
OK, does anyone read Liberty Bell 7? Over.

[Hunt Club 1] Liberty Bell 7, Liberty Bell 7, Hunt Club 1 is 2 miles southwest you. [Cardfile 9] Liberty Bell 7, this is 9 Card File. We have your entry into the water. Will be over you in just about 30 seconds.

Roger, my condition is good; OK, the capsule is floating, slowly coming vertical, have actuated the rescue aids. The reserve chute has jettisoned, in fact I can see it in the water, and the whip antenna should be up.
OK, give me how much longer it'll be before you get here.
This is Hunt Club 1, we are in orbit now at this time, around the capsule.
Roger, give me about another 5 minutes here, to mark these switch positions here, before I give you a call to come in and hook on. Are you ready to come in and hook on anytime?
Hunt Club 1, roger we are ready anytime you are.
OK, give me about another 3 or 4 minutes here to take these switch positions, then I'll be ready for you.
1, wilco.

[This ends the mission. What happens next is that the side hatch fails and jettisons, causing the ship to sink and the CDR to swim out. His suit started to fill up with water, but was picked up. The Liberty Bell 7 craft was recovered in 1999]

Title: MR-4: Liberty Bell 7
Description:
The Mercury-Redstone 4 (Liberty Bell 7) mission is the second U.S. space flight with the goals of testing additional attitude control modes, mans ability to operate in space and verify spacecraft systems.

Astronaut: Gus Grissom
BriefingText:
Mercury-Redstone 4: "Liberty Bell 7"

Mission Objectives:
1. Familiarize man with a brief but complete space flight experience, including the lift-off, powered flight, weightless flight (approximately 5 minutes), re-entry, and landing phases of the flight.
2. Evaluate man's ability to perform as a functional unit during space flight by demonstrating manual control of spacecraft attitude before, during, and after retrofire and by use of voice communications during flight.
3. Study man's physiological reactions during space flight.
4. Qualify the explosively-actuated side egress hatch.

Flight Plan:
00:00 - Lift-off
00:30 - Systems report
01:00 - Systems report
01:15 - Cabin pressure report
01:30 - Systems report
02:00 - Systems report
02:23 - Launch-vehicle engine cutoff & tower sep, retro jettison switch OFF
02:33 - Spacecraft seperation from launch vehicle
02:38 - Spacecraft turnaround to flight attitude on autopilot
03:00 - Transfer of flight control from autopilot to manual proportional control system, and evaluation of system.
04:00 - Spacecraft yawed 45 degrees to left using horixon as attitude reference
05:10 - Retrograde rockets fired manually
05:35 - Retrojettison system armed, transfer of flight control from manual proportinal control system to rate command control system, radio transmitter switched from UHF to HF
06:10 - Retropackage jettison
06:40 - Periscope retracts automatically (can be later in Reentry), spacecraft positioned into reentry attitude.
07:00 - Communications switched back to UHF transmitter
07:46 - Reentry starts
09:41 - Drogue parachute deploy, Snorkels open, Emergency rate oxygen flow
10:13 - Main landing parachute deployment
15:37 - Landing

Mission details:
Commander: Virgil I. "Gus" Grissom
Capsule name: Liberty Bell 7
Booster: Redstone
Mission Profile: Sub-orbital

March 7, 1961: Spacecraft delivered to Hangar S at Cape Canaveral Air Force Station, Florida
July 18, 1961: Original launch date
July 19, 1961: Second launch attempt, cancelled at T-10 minutes due to unfavorable weather
Planned launch time: July 21st 1961 07:20 AM EST
Countdown Start: July 20th 1961 6:00 AM EST PM EST
Capsule Ingress: July 21st 1961 08:58 UTC
Launch: July 21st 1961 at 12:20:36 UTC, after a short hold due to an issue with one of the 70 hatch bolts.

Mission start: 
T -15 minutes with final checks

Notes:
Reentry has desgined a generic capsule with all of the main Mercury features. Some readouts such as voltages, amps, trajectory details etc, might differ from audio. I have tried to recreate the mission to the best of my abilities within the limitation of my sim.

Have a good flight!
